# counts and proportions
for var in categorical_vars:
    counts = df[var].value_counts(dropna=False)
    props = df[var].value_counts(normalize=True, dropna=False).round(4)

    summary = counts.to_frame("count")
    summary["proportion"] = props

    print(f"\nSummary of {var}:")
    print(summary)

Task 6

Data Description

The dataset contains 9,280 rows and 21 columns, capturing client demographics, marketing campaign details, economic indicators, and the target variable y, which indicates whether a client subscribed to a certified term deposit (CD). The dataset includes both numeric variables (such as age, duration, and campaign) and categorical variables (such as day_of_week, loan, and marital status).

Numeric Distribution

The variables duration and campaign both show right-skewed distributions, with most values concentrated at the lower end and a few extreme values creating long tails. Age is also right-skewed, ranging from 17 to 98 with a median of 38, indicating that most clients are middle-aged. Duration, the last contact in seconds, has a median of 265 and a maximum of 4,199, showing that most calls last less than 5 minutes, while a few last much longer. Campaign, representing the number of contacts during the current campaign, has a median of 2 and a maximum of 39, reflecting that most clients are contacted a few times. Similarly, pdays, the number of days since the last contact in a previous campaign, is dominated by the value 999, a placeholder indicating that most clients had not been contacted before.

Categorical Distribution

The target variable y is evenly split, with half of the clients subscribing to a CD and half not. The distribution of day_of_week shows that client contact is highest on Thursdays (21.6%) and lowest on Fridays (19.0%), with Mondays, Tuesdays, and Wednesdays in between. Regarding loan status, most clients (82.8%) do not have a loan, while 14.7% do, and 2.4% are unknown. For marital status, the majority are married (57.5%), followed by single (31.3%) and divorced (11.0%), with a very small fraction (0.2%) unknown.

Numeric Correlation

Correlations among numeric variables show that social and economic indicators are highly interrelated. In particular, euribor3m, emp.var.rate, and nr.employed have very strong positive correlations with each other (above 0.85).

Predictors of Target Variable

Two variables appear to be strong potential predictors of CD subscription. The average duration of the last contact for clients who subscribed was 553 seconds (just over 9 minutes), compared to 222 seconds (just under 4 minutes) for non-subscribers, suggesting that longer calls are associated with positive responses. Similarly, emp.var.rate, the employment variation rate, differs substantially between groups: clients who subscribed are associated with lower values (mean = -1.23, median = -1.8) compared to non-subscribers (mean = 0.24, median = 1.1). These differences indicate that both the length of contact and the economic environment captured by employment variation may influence client decisions.
